<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-762-019  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 762 019.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 17 1989 v6 n28 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber-optic hubs help establish LAN backbones. (David Systems'ExpressNet Fiber Optic Hub, ExpressNet SuperHub) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grygo, Gene.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   David Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   David Systems ExpressNet Fiber Optic Hub (Computer communicationsequipment) (product introduction)David Systems ExpressNet Super-Hub (Computer communicationsequipment) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionFiber OpticsEthernetNetworksCommunications Equipment.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Fiber-Optic Hubs Help Establish LAN BackbonesandM;SUNNYVALE, Calif.andP;  -- David Systems has added two fiber-optic hubs to itsExpressNet Ethernet product line.andP;  ExpressNet Fiber Optic Hub and ExpressNetSuperHub are geared toward helping to create corporate network backbones,according to company officials.andM;The company's own market research and that of Forrester Research ofCambridge, Mass., showed that fiber-optic cabling follows closely behindunshielded twisted-pair wire as the most popular method for creatingcorporate local area networks.andM;&quot;In addition to the increasing reliance on fiber, we've also seeninstallations grow in size to over several hundred users in many instances,&quot;said Phil McDermott, a vice president with David Systems.andM;The hub can link multiple hubs, computers and workstations over a distance ofone kilometer and features four fiber-optic ports per hub.andP;  Each link has twofiber connections: one for transmitting and one for receiving.andP;  Several hubscan be connected to serve network distances of as much as five kilometers.andO;In addition to extending LAN distances, the hub provides protection againstelectrical interference, which sometimes affects large networks.andM;The product includes a small unit called a fiber-optic medium attachment unit(FO-MAU), which is placed beside the second hub or workstation to terminatethe fiber link.andP;  The output of the FO-MAU is a standard attachment unitinterface (AUI) port.andP;  A short AUI cable completes the connection, theofficials said.andM;ExpressNet Fiber Optic Hub also includes four ports for twisted-pair wiringthat can be used to link workstations and other hubs.andP;  The product hasbuilt-in network management at the physical layer for control over individualports.andP;  It also provides diagnostics and gathers statistics for faultdetection and isolation.andM;The SuperHub accommodates multiple twisted-pair and fiber-optic hubs that canbe mounted in a standard 19-inch rack to link more than 100 users from asingle location in a network, the officials said.andM;Rack-mounting for larger configurations of ExpressNet Hubs are provided.andP;  TheSuperHub uses a standard 19-inch rack, in which as many as 10 hubs arelinked, allowing 108 connections to be made from one point.andP;  The SuperHubconfiguration allows the creation of large Ethernet networks of 1,000 userswhen one hub is designated as the primary hub and is connected to afiber-optic or coaxial backbone, bridge or router.andM;ExpressNet Fiber Optic Hub is priced at $1,780; each port is $895.andO;ExpressNet SuperHub is priced at $995.andP;  The associated FO-MAU unit is pricedat $450.andP;  All products are available now.andM;David Systems Inc. can be contacted at 701 E. Evelyn Ave., Sunnyvale, CA94086, (408) 720-8000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>